1 (2) As used in subsection (1) of this section:
2 (a) “Institution” includes state and local correctional facilities, mental health facilities, juvenile
3 detention facilities and state training schools.
4 (b) “Medical facility” means a health care facility as defined in ORS 442.015, a licensed
5 physician’s office or anywhere a licensed medical practitioner provides health care services.
6 (c) “Public utility” has the meaning provided for that term in ORS 757.005 and includes any
7 cooperative, people’s utility district or other municipal corporation providing an electric, gas, water
8 or other utility service.
9 (d) “Railroad” has the meaning provided for that term in ORS 824.020.
10 (e) “Public transportation facility” means any property, structure or equipment used for or in
11 connection with the transportation of persons for hire by rail, air or bus, including any railroad
12 cars, buses or airplanes used to carry out such transportation.
13 (f) [“Telecommunications carrier” has the meaning given that term in ORS 133.721.] “Telecom-
14 munications provider” has the meaning given that term in ORS 184.911.
15 (3) Criminal mischief in the first degree is a Class C felony.
16
17 SCRAP METAL THEFT ALERT SYSTEM
18
19 SECTION 2. Sections 3 to 9 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of ORS 165.116
20 to 165.124.
21 SECTION 3. (1) A law enforcement agency may:
22 (a) Register with the scrap metal theft alert system maintained and provided at no
23 charge to users by the Recycled Materials Association, or its successor organization, or an
24 equivalent scrap metal theft alert system described in administrative rule by the Department
25 of Justice; and
26 (b) Report thefts of metal property to the system that occur within the geographic area
27 over which the law enforcement agency has jurisdiction.
28 (2) The department may adopt rules necessary to administer the provisions of this sec-
29 tion.
30 SECTION 4. A scrap metal business shall:
31 (1) Register with or subscribe to a scrap metal theft alert system described in section 3
32 of this 2026 Act to receive alerts regarding thefts of metal property in the relevant ge-
33 ographic area;
34 (2) Maintain the registration or subscription;
35 (3) On a daily basis, download the scrap metal theft alerts generated by the system;
36 (4) Use the scrap metal theft alerts in conducting all applicable business activity to
37 identify metal property that may be the subject of theft; and
38 (5) Maintain a copy of any scrap metal theft alert for a minimum of 90 days following the
39 date the alert was downloaded under this section.
40
41 SCRAP METAL SELLER REGISTRATION
42
43 SECTION 5. (1)(a) An individual may not sell, trade or contract to sell or trade
44 nonferrous metal property or commercial metal property to a scrap metal business unless
45 the individual is registered as a scrap metal seller with the Department of Justice under
[2]

HB 4140
1 section 7 of this 2026 Act.
2 (b) Notwithstanding paragraph (a) of this subsection, an individual not registered under
3 section 7 of this 2026 Act may sell, trade or contract to sell or trade nonferrous metal
4 property or commercial metal property to a scrap metal business without registering with
5 the department if the aggregate value of the metal property sold or traded does not exceed
6 $ within a 90-day period. The total value of metal property included in a single
7 transaction under this paragraph may not exceed $ .
8 (2) Violation of subsection (1) of this section is a Class A misdemeanor.
9 SECTION 6. Section 5 of this 2026 Act does not apply to:
10 (1) The persons described in ORS 165.124 (1)(a) to (e);
11 (2) A person to whom a license has been issued under ORS 479.630;
12 (3) A person to whom a journeyman plumber license has been issued under ORS 693.030;
13 (4) A person to whom a Section 608 Technician Certification has been issued by the
14 United States Environmental Protection Agency; and
15 (5) Any other similar persons designated by the Department of Justice by rule as a li-
16 censed professional that regularly or periodically sells or delivers metal property to a scrap
17 metal business in the course of the person’s applicable business activity.
18 SECTION 7. (1) An individual is qualified to be registered as a scrap metal seller with the
19 Department of Justice under this section if the individual:
20 (a) Is not prohibited from selling, purchasing, receiving, trading or entering into a con-
21 tract, agreement or pledge to sell, purchase, receive or trade metal property under state or
22 federal law, including successfully completing a background check as described under sub-
23 section (3) of this section;
24 (b) Applies to the department in a form and manner prescribed by the department; and
25 (c) Pays any fee adopted by the department by rule.
26 (2) An application for registration under this section must state the applicant’s legal
27 name, current address and telephone number, date and place of birth, physical description
28 and any additional information determined necessary by department rules.
29 (3)(a) The department shall request that the Department of State Police conduct a
30 criminal background check to determine the eligibility of an individual to be registered under
31 this section by reviewing state and federal databases including the:
32 (A) Oregon computerized criminal history system;
33 (B) Law Enforcement Data System;
34 (C) Databases maintained by the Federal Bureau of Investigation; and
35 (D) National Crime Information Center.
36 (b) An individual is ineligible to be registered under this section if the individual, within
37 five years of the criminal background check, has been convicted of:
38 (A) A felony or misdemeanor for which an essential element is fraud; or
39 (B) Burglary, robbery or theft.
40 (c) For the purpose of requesting a state or nationwide criminal records check under this
41 section, the Department of Justice may require the fingerprints of an individual who applies
42 for registration as a scrap metal seller under this section.
43 (4)(a) Within 30 days of receiving an application for registration as a scrap metal seller
44 under this section, if the department has verified the information contained in the applica-
45 tion and determined that the applicant has met each of the qualifications described in sub-
[3]

HB 4140
1 section (1) of this section, the department shall register the individual as a scrap metal seller
2 and issue proof of registration to the individual.
3 (b) The department may refuse to register an individual as a scrap metal seller under
4 this section or may suspend or revoke the registration if the department determines that the
5 individual violated a provision of this section or a rule adopted by the department under
6 section 9 of this 2026 Act.
7 (5)(a) Registration under this section is valid for one year from the date of registration,
8 unless revoked.
9 (b) An individual may renew an unexpired registration by repeating the procedures set
10 forth in subsection (1) of this section.
11 (6) An individual registered as a scrap metal seller under this section shall:
12 (a) Maintain a copy of the proof of registration as long as the registration is valid.
13 (b) Present a copy of the proof of registration to a scrap metal business when required
14 under ORS 165.117.
15 (7) The department shall establish and maintain an electronic searchable database of all
16 individuals registered as a scrap metal seller under this section. The department shall
17 maintain the database by ensuring that new registrations are added to the database, renewed
18 registrations are assigned a new expiration date and expired or revoked registrations are
19 marked expired or revoked but maintained in the database.
20 SECTION 8. All fees received by the Department of Justice under section 7 of this 2026
21 Act shall be deposited in the Department of Justice Operating Account created in ORS
22 180.180. Amounts deposited under this section are continuously appropriated to the depart-
23 ment to carry out the provisions of sections 6, 7, 8 and 9 of this 2026 Act.
24 SECTION 9. The Department of Justice shall adopt rules necessary to administer the
25 provisions of sections 6, 7, 8 and 9 of this 2026 Act. The rules must:
26 (1) Include procedures for applying for and renewing registration as a scrap metal seller
27 under section 7 of this 2026 Act; and
28 (2) Provide that any fee adopted by the department under section 7 (1)(c) of this 2026 Act
29 be in an amount reasonably calculated to cover the cost of administering the provisions of
30 sections 6, 7, 8 and 9 of this 2026 Act, not to exceed an annual total of $500 per individual.
31 SECTION 10. ORS 165.117 is amended to read:
32 165.117. (1) Before completing a transaction, a scrap metal business engaged in business in this
